8 SECTION 5.(b) The Child Care Commission shall adopt or amend any rules to
9 ensure uniformity and consistency in application of the exemptions for school-age children in
10 out-of-school child care programs as provided in this section.
11 SECTION 6. G.S. 110-91(7)a. reads as rewritten:
12 "a. The Commission shall adopt rules for child care centers regarding
13 staff-child ratios, group sizes and multi-age groupings other than for
14 infants and toddlers, provided that these rules shall be no less stringent
15 than those currently required for staff-child ratios as enacted in Section
16 156(e) of Chapter 757 of the 1985 Session Laws. Each lead teacher
17 shall support no more than two groups.
18 1. Except as otherwise provided in this subdivision, the
19 staff-child ratios and group sizes for infants and toddlers in
20 child care centers shall be no more than as follows:
21 Age Ratio Staff/Children Group Size
22 0 to 12 months 1/5 1015
23 12 to 24 months 1/6 1218
24 2 to 3 years 1/10 20.
25 No child care center shall care for more than 25 children in one
26 group. Child care centers providing care for 26 or more
27 children shall provide for two or more groups according to the
28 ages of children and shall provide separate supervisory
29 personnel and separate identifiable space for each group.
30 1a. If a child care center is operating under voluntary enhanced
31 requirements, the maximum group size for toddlers aged 2 to
32 3 years may be increased from 18 to 20 children when the child
33 care center maintains a 1/9 staff-child ratio.
34 1b. If a child care center is operating under the highest voluntary
35 enhanced requirements, the child care center may use the
36 following maximum group sizes for infants and toddlers when
37 the child care center maintains staff-child ratios as provided
38 herein:
39 Age Ratio Staff/Children Group Size
40 0 to 12 months 1/4 12
41 12 to 24 months 1/5 15
42 2 to 3 years 1/8 20.
43 1c. A child care center director can assign a floater to relieve one
44 teacher at a time for 0- to 24-month old age groups provided
45 the floater meets the federal requirements to care for infants or
46 holds an Early Education credential or higher educational
47 level.
48 …."
49 SECTION 7.(a) G.S. 110-91(8) reads as rewritten:
50 "(8) Qualifications for Staff. – Qualifications for child care staff are as follows:
House Bill 412-Second Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. All child care center administrators shall be at least 21 years of age.
2 All child care center administrators shall have the North Carolina
3 Early Childhood Administration Credential or its equivalent as
4 determined by the Department. All child care administrators
5 performing administrative duties as of the date this act becomes law
6 and child care administrators who assume administrative duties at any
7 time after this act becomes law and until September 1, 1998, shall
8 obtain the required credential by September 1, 2000. Child care
9 administrators who assume administrative duties after September 1,
10 1998, shall begin working toward the completion of the North Carolina
11 Early Childhood Administration Credential or its equivalent within six
12 months after assuming administrative duties and shall complete the
13 credential or its equivalent within two years after beginning work to
14 complete the credential. Each child care center shall be under the
15 direction or supervision of a person meeting these requirements. All
16 staff counted toward meeting the required staff-child ratio shall be at
17 least 16 years of age, provided that persons younger than 18 years of
18 age work under the direct supervision of a credentialed staff person
19 who is at least 21 years of age.
20 b. All lead teachers in a child care center shall have at least a North
21 Carolina Early Childhood Credential or its equivalent as determined
22 by the Department. Lead teachers shall either (i) be enrolled in the
23 North Carolina Early Childhood Credential coursework or its
24 equivalent as determined by the Department within six months after
25 becoming employed as a lead teacher or within six months after this
26 act becomes law, whichever is later, and shall complete the credential
27 or its equivalent within 18 months after enrollment.enrollment or (ii)
28 have a minimum of five years of documented experience teaching in a
29 licensed child care facility in this State which shall be deemed
30 equivalent to the North Carolina Early Childhood Credential.
31 c. Only administrators and lead teachers in licensed child care centers are
32 required to have a North Carolina Early Childhood Credential or its
33 equivalent as determined by the Department. All other staff shall meet
34 the standards established by the Commission for their positions that do
35 not include a North Carolina Early Childhood Credential or its
36 equivalent as determined by the Department.
37 d. For child care centers licensed to care for 200 or more children, the
38 Department, in collaboration with the North Carolina Institute for
39 Early Childhood Professional Development, shall establish categories
40 to recognize the levels of education achieved by child care center
41 administrators and teachers who perform administrative functions.
42 The Department shall use these categories to establish appropriate
43 staffing based on the size of the center and the individual staff
44 responsibilities.
45 e. Effective January 1, 1998, an operator of a licensed family child care
46 home shall be at least 21 years old and have a high school diploma or
47 its equivalent. Operators of a family child care home licensed prior to
48 January 1, 1998, shall be at least 18 years of age and literate. Literate
49 is defined as understanding licensing requirements and having the
50 ability to communicate with the family and relevant emergency
