1 personnel. Any operator of a licensed family child care home shall be
2 the person on-site providing child care.
3 f. The Commission shall adopt standards to establish appropriate
4 qualifications for all staff in child care centers. These standards shall
5 reflect training, experience, education and credentialing and shall be
6 appropriate for the size center and the level of individual staff
7 responsibilities. It is the intent of this provision to guarantee that all
8 children in child care are cared for by qualified people. Pursuant to
9 G.S. 110-106, no requirements may interfere with the teachings or
10 doctrine of any established religious organization. The staff
11 qualification requirements of this subdivision do not apply to
12 religious-sponsored child care facilities pursuant to G.S. 110-106."
13 SECTION 7.(b) Recognizing the need to maintain critical health, safety, and welfare
14 standards for child care and that the main determinants of quality in child care are positive
15 adult-child interactions and an environment free of toxic stress and adverse childhood
16 experiences, the Child Care Commission shall develop standards for infant and toddler care
17 provider staff in licensed child care facilities caring for infants and toddlers from birth to 24
18 months old which provides infant and toddler care provider staff the option to either (i) meet all
19 of the federal health and safety requirements tied to the Child Care and Development Block Grant
20 (CCDBG) funding, including CPR and SIDS training and age-appropriate health and safety
21 training requirements set by the North Carolina Child Care Commission, or (ii) hold an Early
22 Childhood credential.
23 SECTION 8. Section 8 of S.L. 2024-34 is amended by adding a new subsection to
24 read:
25 "SECTION 8.(a1) In modifying the quality rating improvement system (QRIS), the Division
26 of Child Development and Early Education shall ensure a North Carolina Early Childhood
27 Credential based on five years of work experience in a licensed child care facility in this State is
28 treated as equivalent to when that credential is earned through other pathways for purposes of
29 awarding a star-rating."
30 SECTION 9. The Weikart Youth Program Quality Assessment ("Weikart Program")
31 shall be added as an assessment tool for evaluating out-of-school child care programs and
32 awarding of a star-rating. The Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Child
33 Development and Early Education, shall complete the necessary crosswalk evaluation of the
34 Weikart Program and have it available for applicants to use not later than one year after the date
35 this act becomes law.
36 SECTION 10. Notwithstanding any other provision of law, rule, or regulation, the
37 Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Child Development and Early Education
38 (Division), shall, for courses offered by a community college in the North Carolina Community
39 Colleges System (NCCCS), assign credit for continuing education courses on the same basis as
40 curriculum courses designated by NCCCS as equivalent to the continuing education courses for
41 the purpose of providing any credential offered by the Division.
42 SECTION 11. The Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Child
43 Development and Early Education, shall:
44 (1) Not later than December 1, 2025, and in consultation with the North Carolina
45 Community Colleges System, create a North Carolina School
46 Age/Out-of-School Care Credential that aligns with a new curriculum course
47 and continuing education course entitled "Introduction to School Age Care
48 and Education."
49 (2) Award the North Carolina Early Childhood Administration Credential or the
50 North Carolina Family Child Care Credential to individuals who have
51 successfully completed continuing education courses that are equivalent to
House Bill 412-Second Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 child care curriculum courses, as determined by the Community Colleges
2 System. The Community Colleges System shall ensure that the continuing
3 education courses are comparable to the corresponding curriculum courses in
4 course descriptions, competencies, and hour requirements and shall state the
5 credential that is to be awarded for each continuing education course.
6 SECTION 12.(a) The Commissioner of the Department of Insurance shall establish
7 a workgroup to examine the potential for developing group liability insurance plan opportunities
8 for all child care providers. The workgroup shall consist of representatives from all of the
9 following:
10 (1) The Department of Insurance.
11 (2) The insurance industry.
12 (3) The child care industry, including foster family homes and out-of-school
13 providers.
14 (4) The Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Child
15 Development and Early Education.
16 (5) The American Tort Reform Association.
17 SECTION 12.(b) The workgroup shall develop findings and recommendations
18 related to at least the following:
19 (1) Potential methods for creating group liability insurance plan opportunities for
20 all child care providers.
21 (2) Reforms that could reduce group liability insurance plan premiums.
22 (3) Tort reforms that could reduce the liability damages of child care providers.
23 SECTION 12.(c) By January 1, 2026, the Department of Insurance shall report the
24 findings and recommendations of the workgroup to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee
25 on Health and Human Services, the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on General
26 Government, and the Fiscal Research Division.
27 SECTION 13. The Child Care Commission shall adopt or amend any rules to ensure
28 uniformity and consistency in application of the provisions of this act.
29
30 PART III. EFFECTIVE DATE
31 SECTION 14. This act is effective when it becomes law.
